diff:1619318272:1619318272:=1,56d0%0a%3c :Category: MorphosyntacticDiversity%0a%3c :Expansion: More examples of the habitual "be" %0a%3c :Author: BrandonW%0a%3c :Original: [[Articles.HabitualBe|HabitualBe]] %0a%3c :OriginalAuthor: [[Profiles.xiranw|xiranw]]%0a%3c :Section: C%0a%3c :Completed: 24.04.2021 - 19:37%0a%3c :Status: ungraded%0a%3c %0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeExpansion:)%0a%3c (:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Grading History'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#history]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#historyend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c %25red%25 '''Comments to student'''%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#comments]]%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#commentsend]]%0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c ----%0a%3c !!%0a%3c %0a%3c %0a%3c ----%0a%3c [[#content]]%0a%3c %0a%3c There are examples of the habitual "be" that can be found in past literature, such as the ones presented below.%0a%3c %0a%3c In Mos Def's album "Black on Both Sides", song "Rock n Roll":%0a%3c %0a%3c "When I get down in my zone%0a%3c I BE rockin Bad Brains and Fishbone.%0a%3c I ain't tryin to slow your groove%0a%3c But that ain't the way I'm tryin to move.%0a%3c I don't turn on Korn to get it on;%0a%3c I BE playin Jimi Hendrix 'til the dawn."%0a%3c %0a%3c In Daniel Black's book "The Sacred Place":%0a%3c %0a%3c "'You don't get tired o' Momma beatin' you?' Jerry asked him one day.%0a%3c "'She don't really BE mad,' Enoch explained lovingly. 'Dat's jes what she suppose to do. Sometime she BE laughin' as she BE beatin' me.'"%0a%3c %0a%3c Looking at the example "I BE playin Jimi Hendrix 'til the dawn." specifically, the Standard American English version of this example would be "I am always playing Jimi Hendrix 'til the dawn." Hence, the habitual "be" is used to express how often Mos Def plays Jimi Hendrix's music.%0a%3c %0a%3c Source: https://www.thoughtco.com/invariant-be-verb-term-1691187#:~:text=%2522The%2520best%2520known%2520syntactic%2520feature,He%2520be%2520tired.%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a%3c (:C